01:05:01,065 --> 01:05:02,699
Everybody here knows it.

1294
01:05:02,732 --> 01:05:05,302
But, there's nothing
more I can do.

1295
01:05:05,335 --> 01:05:07,071
Maybe next time, son.

1296
01:05:08,572 --> 01:05:11,808
Now I've got the second
shift starting in 15 minutes,

1297
01:05:11,841 --> 01:05:14,044
and I reckon I can use
you two on that shift.

1298
01:05:14,078 --> 01:05:17,047
That is if you could
still use a day's work,

1299
01:05:17,081 --> 01:05:18,882
but you guys look a mess.

1300
01:05:18,915 --> 01:05:21,218
Go get changed into
some clean uniforms

1301
01:05:21,251 --> 01:05:23,988
and head out to the
station with the new crew.

1302
01:05:24,021 --> 01:05:25,855
- Yes, sir.
- Yes, sir.

1303
01:05:27,091 --> 01:05:28,792
I tell you right
now, reverend.

1304
01:05:28,825 --> 01:05:30,860
We've got to do something!

1305
01:05:30,894 --> 01:05:32,963
We just can't sit around
here and let these monsters

1306
01:05:32,997 --> 01:05:35,399
abduct and murder our children.

1307
01:05:35,432 --> 01:05:37,234
(clapping)

1308
01:05:37,267 --> 01:05:41,238
And, just exactly what would
you have us do, Greg huh?

1309
01:05:41,271 --> 01:05:44,574
What in Jesus's name can we do?

1310
01:05:44,608 --> 01:05:48,545
If we retaliate, we'll all
be dead before sundown.

1311
01:05:48,578 --> 01:05:51,915
I suggest we just
stay out the way

1312
01:05:51,948 --> 01:05:54,084
and let things blow over.

1313
01:05:54,118 --> 01:05:55,852
Blow over?

1314
01:05:55,885 --> 01:05:58,488
Man, they done damn near
killed this boy right here,

1315
01:05:58,522 --> 01:06:00,424
ain't no telling what
in the hell they've done

1316
01:06:00,457 --> 01:06:02,192
to these people
here, and you want

1317
01:06:02,226 --> 01:06:03,493
to let it blow over?

1318
01:06:03,527 --> 01:06:05,195
Hell that could've
been one of our kids,

1319
01:06:05,229 --> 01:06:08,098
could've been one of
your kids or your kids.

1320
01:06:08,132 --> 01:06:10,267
And, even yours
Reverend Aberdeen.

1321
01:06:10,300 --> 01:06:13,070
And, this all because
the color of our skin.

1322
01:06:13,103 --> 01:06:16,240
Well I say we don't
just sit back.

1323
01:06:16,273 --> 01:06:18,575
We've gots to do something
before they slowly

1324
01:06:18,608 --> 01:06:21,278
but surely wipe out
what's left of us.

1325
01:06:21,311 --> 01:06:23,113
You know what, damn
it, I'm pissed now!

1326
01:06:23,147 --> 01:06:24,514
I'm mad as hell.

1327
01:06:24,548 --> 01:06:26,083
We've got to do something.

1328
01:06:26,116 --> 01:06:28,718
I say let's take
the fight to them!

1329
01:06:28,752 --> 01:06:31,121
Let's take the fight to them!

1330
01:06:31,155 --> 01:06:33,890
Let's take the drama to
their mamas, how 'bout that?

1331
01:06:33,923 --> 01:06:35,125
See how it feel, huh!

1332
01:06:35,159 --> 01:06:37,894
Let's take the heat
and not damn retreat.

1333
01:06:37,927 --> 01:06:41,965
Let's bring the thunder
and let them wonder.

1334
01:06:41,998 --> 01:06:44,968
And, let's bring the
pain and make it rain.

1335
01:06:45,001 --> 01:06:47,471
(clapping)

1336
01:06:47,504 --> 01:06:49,073
Y'all crazy.

1337
01:06:49,106 --> 01:06:51,141
You gonna get yourself killed.

1338
01:06:51,175 --> 01:06:52,742
No, Mr. Montgomery.

1339
01:06:52,776 --> 01:06:54,478
Hey, now that's what
I'm talking about.

1340
01:06:54,511 --> 01:06:56,813
(laughing)

1341
01:06:56,846 --> 01:06:58,982
You done ignited a fire
inside me this afternoon,

1342
01:06:59,015 --> 01:07:00,284
Mr. Parsons.

1343
01:07:00,317 --> 01:07:01,451
Huh?

1344
01:07:01,485 --> 01:07:03,125
I'm gonna be following
right behind you.

1345
01:07:03,153 --> 01:07:04,421
Follow me?

1346
01:07:04,454 --> 01:07:07,824
Oh hell no, I'm too
old for this shit.

1347
01:07:07,857 --> 01:07:10,127
I was just giving y'all
some ideas of some stuff

1348
01:07:10,160 --> 01:07:11,328
y'all can do.

1349
01:07:11,361 --> 01:07:13,330
I'm gonna sit my black
ass down over there,

1350
01:07:13,363 --> 01:07:14,764
and I'm gonna pray for y'all.

1351
01:07:14,798 --> 01:07:17,601
Reverend Aberdeen gonna
lead y'all to victory.

1352
01:07:17,634 --> 01:07:20,104
Aint' that right,
Reverend Aberdeen?

1353
01:07:20,137 --> 01:07:22,906
Ain't that right,
Reverend Aberdeen?

1354
01:07:22,939 --> 01:07:25,075
I said ain't that right,
Reverend Aberdeen,

1355
01:07:25,109 --> 01:07:27,077
ain't that right?

1356
01:07:27,111 --> 01:07:28,212
Say Jarvis?

1357
01:07:29,179 --> 01:07:30,179
Yeah.

1358
01:07:31,381 --> 01:07:34,851
Man, I'm really
sorry about everything.

1359
01:07:36,653 --> 01:07:40,824
I mean the promotion, all the
trouble I caused you today.

1360
01:07:44,394 --> 01:07:48,198
I know it's my fault you
didn't get that job today.

1361
01:07:48,232 --> 01:07:51,735
I never wanted things
to end up like this.

1362
01:07:53,137 --> 01:07:55,539
And, all because I
was too lazy to take

1363
01:07:55,572 --> 01:07:57,841
the safe route to get here.

1364
01:08:00,244 --> 01:08:04,047
You know Jericho, don't
even worry about it.

1365
01:08:07,016 --> 01:08:10,454
I mean you are lazy, but none
of this could've happened

1366
01:08:10,487 --> 01:08:12,088
if I didn't let it.

1367
01:08:14,023 --> 01:08:15,692
Could've put my foot
down and stopped us

1368
01:08:15,725 --> 01:08:19,196
from going through
Mr. Edwards's land.

1369
01:08:19,229 --> 01:08:22,732
Oh you don't think I
could've stopped you?

1370
01:08:24,734 --> 01:08:26,336
Look I know I like
to play it safe,

1371
01:08:26,370 --> 01:08:30,207
but I guess at the end
of the day, I just want

1372
01:08:32,041 --> 01:08:34,043
to take a leap of faith.

1373
01:08:35,779 --> 01:08:38,348
And, I appreciate you for
being that loose cannon

1374
01:08:38,382 --> 01:08:41,084
that always pushed me, you know?

1375
01:08:42,286 --> 01:08:45,789
Always ready and willing
to take a chance.

1376
01:08:49,459 --> 01:08:51,928
I mean things didn't
work out, but just think

1377
01:08:51,961 --> 01:08:52,961
if it did.

1378
01:08:56,633 --> 01:08:59,035
Look in this messed
up world we live in

1379
01:08:59,068 --> 01:09:00,870
every Negro around
here is scared,

1380
01:09:00,904 --> 01:09:03,940
scared to take a
chance, and as a result,

1381
01:09:03,973 --> 01:09:07,411
there ain't no progress
being made, none.

1382
01:09:10,480 --> 01:09:13,783
This town needs more
men just like you.

1383
01:09:15,219 --> 01:09:16,786
Yeah, just like you

1384
01:09:18,322 --> 01:09:20,957
who ain't scared,
scared to take a chance,

1385
01:09:20,990 --> 01:09:24,561
who ain't afraid of the
dangers around the corner

1386
01:09:24,594 --> 01:09:26,763
or the road less traveled.

1387
01:09:30,467 --> 01:09:34,638
Whatever the case, I'm just
thankful you're my best friend.

1388
01:09:34,671 --> 01:09:36,740
(crying)

1389
01:09:38,442 --> 01:09:41,278
I mean you did
save my life today.

1390
01:09:42,279 --> 01:09:43,279
I did.

1391
01:09:44,781 --> 01:09:47,717
Look finish getting dressed.

1392
01:09:47,751 --> 01:09:48,994
I'm gonna go on
out and get started

1393
01:09:49,018 --> 01:09:51,255
on prepping the machine.

1394
01:09:51,288 --> 01:09:52,556
All right man.

1395
01:09:52,589 --> 01:09:55,659
Don't wanna screw this
second chance we got.

1396
01:09:55,692 --> 01:09:58,495
One thing I know for
sure ain't no third shit

1397
01:09:58,528 --> 01:10:00,497
around this place.

1398
01:10:00,530 --> 01:10:02,165
Man, you got that shit right.

1399
01:10:02,198 --> 01:10:03,933
All right, I'll
see you out there.

1400
01:10:03,967 --> 01:10:06,303
Thank you, man, thank you.

1401
01:10:17,347 --> 01:10:21,651
♪ I waited all my life

1402
01:10:21,685 --> 01:10:26,690
♪ To find a reason why

1403
01:10:27,624 --> 01:10:32,161
♪ Am far too tired to fight

1404
01:10:32,195 --> 01:10:37,200
♪ I couldn't even try

1405
01:10:38,402 --> 01:10:41,137
♪ Broken in a way

1406
01:10:41,170 --> 01:10:44,374
♪ No one could ever know

1407
01:10:44,408 --> 01:10:46,209
Jericho, your
friend's in trouble.

1408
01:10:46,242 --> 01:10:47,387
These white men are after 'em.

1409
01:10:47,411 --> 01:10:49,879
I think they're gonna kill him.

1410
01:10:49,913 --> 01:10:51,848
Baby, it's gonna be
all right, I promise you.

1411
01:10:51,881 --> 01:10:53,883
Now you wait right here.

1412
01:10:56,085 --> 01:10:57,463
What the hell's all
the damn commotion

1413
01:10:57,487 --> 01:10:59,889
going on around here?

1414
01:10:59,923 --> 01:11:01,558
Hit him, boy, hit him!

1415
01:11:01,591 --> 01:11:04,528
(fleshy crunching)

1416
01:11:05,762 --> 01:11:06,762
Jericho?

1417
01:11:08,164 --> 01:11:09,699
Jericho?

1418
01:11:09,733 --> 01:11:12,436
(dramatic music)

1419
01:11:15,939 --> 01:11:16,939
Help!

1420
01:11:18,174 --> 01:11:19,174
Marcel?

1421
01:11:20,276 --> 01:11:22,379
What's the meaning of all this?

1422
01:11:22,412 --> 01:11:23,589
You have no right to
come on this property

1423
01:11:23,613 --> 01:11:24,748
and do this to my workers!

1424
01:11:24,781 --> 01:11:25,882
I'll have you arrested!

1425
01:11:25,915 --> 01:11:28,117
(grunting)

1426
01:11:30,454 --> 01:11:33,323
Wait, I'm on your side, shit!

1427
01:11:33,357 --> 01:11:35,692
(grumbling)

1428
01:11:42,799 --> 01:11:46,736
[Reverend Aberdeen] All
right Buford, let him go.

1429
01:11:46,770 --> 01:11:49,573
Clark, this ain't your fight.

1430
01:11:49,606 --> 01:11:53,777
I suggest y'all go back
and mind your own business.

1431
01:11:55,912 --> 01:11:58,047
Man, what the
hell is going on?

1432
01:11:58,081 --> 01:12:00,550
(tense music)

1433
01:12:00,584 --> 01:12:02,218
(gun firing)

1434
01:12:02,251 --> 01:12:04,754
(tense music)

1435
01:12:08,825 --> 01:12:10,293
Get your hands off that boy.

1436
01:12:10,326 --> 01:12:13,129
Ain't you got no
respect for human life?

1437
01:12:13,162 --> 01:12:15,599
I oughta blow your
Goddamn brains out

1438
01:12:15,632 --> 01:12:16,976
for all the heartache
you guys done caused

1439
01:12:17,000 --> 01:12:18,234
around here.

1440
01:12:18,267 --> 01:12:20,470
Am I hearing you
correctly, sir?

1441
01:12:20,504 --> 01:12:22,548
If you'd've hung this nigger
when you were supposed to,

1442
01:12:22,572 --> 01:12:24,240
we wouldn't be here.

1443
01:12:24,273 --> 01:12:26,643
Now I don't know
how he got loose,

1444
01:12:26,676 --> 01:12:30,647
but I reckon he ain't
gonna get away this time.

1445
01:12:30,680 --> 01:12:32,749
Why didn't you kill him?

1446
01:12:32,782 --> 01:12:35,819
I guess 'cause deep
down I ain't no killer,

1447
01:12:35,852 --> 01:12:39,556
and besides we got
a lot in common.

1448
01:12:39,589 --> 01:12:40,824
(laughing)

1449
01:12:40,857 --> 01:12:41,858
Oh really?

1450
01:12:42,992 --> 01:12:46,463
What could you two
possibly have in common?

1451
01:12:46,496 --> 01:12:49,499
You just can't kill him, and
I'm gonna leave it at that.

1452
01:12:49,533 --> 01:12:50,434
[Marcel] Why?

1453
01:12:50,467 --> 01:12:51,935
I'm gonna tell you why!

1454
01:12:51,968 --> 01:12:54,704
(dramatic music)

1455
01:13:03,847 --> 01:13:06,082
'Cause it's gonna take
all that you've got

1456
01:13:06,115 --> 01:13:08,518
to stop this boy from
killing your ass,

1457
01:13:08,552 --> 01:13:11,788
and I mean that in
a good Christian way

1458
01:13:13,222 --> 01:13:15,091
especially this one right here.

1459
01:13:15,124 --> 01:13:17,494
Boy, y'all damn
near killed today,

1460
01:13:17,527 --> 01:13:19,028
this man only son.

1461
01:13:21,397 --> 01:13:24,367
He don't talk too
much, but one thing

1462
01:13:24,400 --> 01:13:25,835
we know for sure.

1463
01:13:26,903 --> 01:13:29,272
He ain't too happy.

1464
01:13:29,305 --> 01:13:31,808
(tense music)

1465
01:13:34,644 --> 01:13:36,713
Get him, boy, get him!

1466
01:13:36,746 --> 01:13:37,547
Yeah!

1467
01:13:37,581 --> 01:13:39,182
(tense music)

1468
01:13:39,215 --> 01:13:41,485
(grunting)

1469
01:13:42,486 --> 01:13:43,887
Get him, baby!

1470
01:13:43,920 --> 01:13:45,731
You make sure you make
them pay for what they did

1471
01:13:45,755 --> 01:13:46,755
to our boy.

1472
01:13:47,557 --> 01:13:49,225
(smacking)

1473
01:13:49,258 --> 01:13:51,661
(grunting)

1474
01:13:51,695 --> 01:13:53,930
(smacking)

1475
01:13:56,900 --> 01:13:57,967
You get back here!

1476
01:13:58,001 --> 01:13:59,402
Get him, baby.

1477
01:13:59,435 --> 01:14:02,739
All right Buford, I think
they had about enough.

1478
01:14:02,772 --> 01:14:04,874
Well maybe just a
little bit more.

1479
01:14:04,908 --> 01:14:06,876
(tense music)

1480
01:14:06,910 --> 01:14:09,546
(smacking)

1481
01:14:09,579 --> 01:14:12,081
(tense music)

1482
01:14:13,917 --> 01:14:15,418
Come on Buford, get him.

1483
01:14:15,451 --> 01:14:16,252
Come on Buford, get him.

1484
01:14:16,285 --> 01:14:17,086
Get him, Buford.

1485
01:14:17,120 --> 01:14:18,888
Come on, man.

1486
01:14:18,922 --> 01:14:19,956
Stop, stop.

1487
01:14:21,625 --> 01:14:22,625
Stop!

1488
01:14:25,294 --> 01:14:28,665
Now many years ago, I
tried to keep my boy

1489
01:14:28,698 --> 01:14:32,268
from standing up for
anything that was right.

1490
01:14:32,301 --> 01:14:34,270
I guess I just didn't
think that things

1491
01:14:34,303 --> 01:14:36,873
could ever get
better for Negroes.

1492
01:14:36,906 --> 01:14:41,277
Maybe I didn't want him to
know how proud I was of him.

1493
01:14:41,310 --> 01:14:43,312
So I never said nothing.

1494
01:14:45,081 --> 01:14:47,551
Now that's my grand baby
you know was hurting,

1495
01:14:47,584 --> 01:14:49,919
and he didn't do
nothing but try to walk

1496
01:14:49,953 --> 01:14:51,788
in his daddy's footsteps.

1497
01:14:51,821 --> 01:14:55,992
Now Thomas was the best
employee this factory ever had.

1498
01:14:57,561 --> 01:15:02,265
He told me how he helped build
it up to what it is today.

1499
01:15:02,298 --> 01:15:04,601
I was scared that
y'all'd do to him

1500
01:15:04,634 --> 01:15:06,269
what y'all's doing to Jarvis.

1501
01:15:06,302 --> 01:15:09,739
So I never let him
know that he was good,

1502
01:15:10,640 --> 01:15:12,308
but it was too late.

1503
01:15:13,677 --> 01:15:14,744
He was great.

1504
01:15:16,179 --> 01:15:20,349
He was God's gift to me, his
family, and this factory.

1505
01:15:26,022 --> 01:15:28,491
And, they made us pay for it.

1506
01:15:30,594 --> 01:15:34,764
I lost two people that I
loved behind this foolishness.

1507
01:15:37,200 --> 01:15:41,137
So I know the pain
that she speaks of.

1508
01:15:41,170 --> 01:15:45,341
You see when you've gone
through so much for so long,

1509
01:15:47,210 --> 01:15:51,114
you grab ahold of
anger and bitterness,

1510
01:15:51,147 --> 01:15:55,318
and then it becomes your
friend, and it shields ya.

1511
01:15:56,720 --> 01:16:00,824
It shields ya so that you
don't feel the hurt anymore.

1512
01:16:02,558 --> 01:16:06,229
But, it also keeps the
good from getting in.

1513
01:16:08,197 --> 01:16:12,368
Now here y'all are still
hanging onto the bitterness

1514
01:16:14,137 --> 01:16:15,137
and anger.

1515
01:16:16,505 --> 01:16:19,242
Shame on ya, shame
on all of you.

1516
01:16:24,080 --> 01:16:25,915
You're just like them.

1517
01:16:28,084 --> 01:16:31,520
Now this thing has
got to stop right now.

1518
01:16:34,891 --> 01:16:36,059
She's right.

1519
01:16:37,661 --> 01:16:41,665
Them two were in my
diner earlier today,

1520
01:16:41,698 --> 01:16:45,869
and that man, he asked that
other man to marry his daughter.

1521
01:16:49,605 --> 01:16:52,375
And, I ain't never been
too fond of Negroes,

1522
01:16:52,408 --> 01:16:57,246
but well I figure if he's
good enough for his daughter,

1523
01:16:57,280 --> 01:17:00,416
maybe we oughta give this
idea of us all getting along

1524
01:17:00,449 --> 01:17:01,885
another look.

1525
01:17:01,918 --> 01:17:06,222
So starting tomorrow, y'all
are welcome in my diner.

1526
01:17:06,255 --> 01:17:07,390
(clapping)

1527
01:17:07,423 --> 01:17:09,759
[Grandma] Thank you Jesus.

1528
01:17:11,928 --> 01:17:14,630
(dramatic music)

1529
01:17:15,965 --> 01:17:16,966
Daddy, no.

1530
01:17:19,769 --> 01:17:22,205
Mildred, you're not
supposed to be here.

1531
01:17:22,238 --> 01:17:23,072
Go on now.

1532
01:17:23,106 --> 01:17:25,274
Why daddy, why?

1533
01:17:25,308 --> 01:17:27,576
Is it because they look like me?

1534
01:17:27,610 --> 01:17:30,279
Are you ashamed of me, of mommy?

1535
01:17:33,316 --> 01:17:34,784
Well I'll be damned.

1536
01:17:34,818 --> 01:17:37,286
Take her out of here.

1537
01:17:37,320 --> 01:17:38,788
You don't understand.

1538
01:17:38,822 --> 01:17:40,456
That's different.

1539
01:17:40,489 --> 01:17:41,791
I gotta protect what's mine.

1540
01:17:41,825 --> 01:17:44,093
I gotta protect our future.

1541
01:17:45,494 --> 01:17:48,464
That nigger mama of
yours was asking for it.

1542
01:17:48,497 --> 01:17:50,399
You monster!

1543
01:17:50,433 --> 01:17:51,667
She mine now.

1544
01:17:52,769 --> 01:17:55,471
Mildred is mine, Agnes is mine.

1545
01:17:55,504 --> 01:17:59,675
Just like little Cody, I
gotta protect him from y'all.

1546
01:18:03,179 --> 01:18:07,416
I'm just a scared old
Negro from Minden Hall.

1547
01:18:07,450 --> 01:18:11,254
I'm a real bad shot,
and I got terrible aim.

1548
01:18:11,287 --> 01:18:13,489
But, here's what
I got going for me

1549
01:18:13,522 --> 01:18:16,325
at the particular moment.

1550
01:18:16,359 --> 01:18:20,329
I got this big ass gun
to the back of your head

1551
01:18:20,363 --> 01:18:22,866
so I can't miss it if I tried.

1552
01:18:23,967 --> 01:18:25,501
Nigger, you ain't
got it in you.

1553
01:18:25,534 --> 01:18:28,738
Oh, he ain't the one
you got to worry about.

1554
01:18:28,772 --> 01:18:30,940
And, I won't hesitate.

1555
01:18:30,974 --> 01:18:33,743
Just go ahead and try me.

1556
01:18:33,777 --> 01:18:36,312
Y'all can just go to hell.

1557
01:18:36,345 --> 01:18:38,547
(smacking)

1558
01:18:40,616 --> 01:18:44,020
Greg, you know my
gun wasn't even loaded?

1559
01:18:44,053 --> 01:18:46,322
Shit, mine wasn't either.

1560
01:18:47,456 --> 01:18:49,192
But, the ass end
of the snug nose is

1561
01:18:49,225 --> 01:18:50,827
one hit or quit, ain't it?

1562
01:18:50,860 --> 01:18:52,428
I knocked the hell out of that.

1563
01:18:52,461 --> 01:18:53,863
I knocked his monkey ass out.

1564
01:18:53,897 --> 01:18:56,365
(laughing)

1565
01:18:56,399 --> 01:18:58,534
[Sheriff] Let me through.

1566
01:18:58,567 --> 01:19:02,305
Sheriff, these
men are responsible

1567
01:19:02,338 --> 01:19:05,341
for the torture
of this young boy.

1568
01:19:05,374 --> 01:19:08,044
I saw the whole damn
thing, and I wouldn't be

1569
01:19:08,077 --> 01:19:10,513
surprised if they
kidnapped and murdered

1570
01:19:10,546 --> 01:19:13,216
other Negroes in the
surrounding community.

1571
01:19:13,249 --> 01:19:15,518
You willing to
testify to that, sir?

1572
01:19:15,551 --> 01:19:17,887
You damn right I will.

1573
01:19:17,921 --> 01:19:21,324
Long as they keep
making this damn paint.

1574
01:19:22,491 --> 01:19:24,994
[Sheriff] Sir, I don't
think I got your name.

1575
01:19:25,028 --> 01:19:26,262
Dale Stevens.

1576
01:19:27,663 --> 01:19:29,565
That is the weirdest thing.

1577
01:19:29,598 --> 01:19:31,667
There used to be an
old used car salesman

1578
01:19:31,700 --> 01:19:33,636
I used to listen
to when I was a kid

1579
01:19:33,669 --> 01:19:35,704
with that exact same
name, and you sound

1580
01:19:35,738 --> 01:19:38,074
just like him, any relation?

1581
01:19:41,344 --> 01:19:43,079
I never heard of the guy.

1582
01:19:43,112 --> 01:19:45,748
Anyway, you take care, sir.

1583
01:19:45,781 --> 01:19:47,416
You too, sheriff.

1584
01:19:57,626 --> 01:19:59,695
[Mr. Munson] Come on, Jarvis.

1585
01:19:59,728 --> 01:20:01,764
Thank you, Mr. Munson.

1586
01:20:01,797 --> 01:20:02,765
Thank you.

1587
01:20:02,798 --> 01:20:05,368
Here let's get
that off of you.

1588
01:20:07,603 --> 01:20:10,773
Well son, Thomas
Cook was your father?

1589
01:20:10,806 --> 01:20:14,277
Yes sir, he taught
me everything I know.

1590
01:20:14,310 --> 01:20:17,113
I haven't heard that
name in almost 20 years

1591
01:20:17,146 --> 01:20:18,681
which is about as
long as he's been

1592
01:20:18,714 --> 01:20:21,450
with the Lord I suppose.

1593
01:20:21,484 --> 01:20:24,287
So many Cooks around here,
I never would've guessed.

1594
01:20:24,320 --> 01:20:27,256
Thomas Cook was not only the
best paper press operator

1595
01:20:27,290 --> 01:20:30,026
I've ever seen, but he was
one of the very best men

1596
01:20:30,059 --> 01:20:31,294
I ever knew.

1597
01:20:31,327 --> 01:20:33,429
Hell he trained me.

1598
01:20:33,462 --> 01:20:36,232
If it wasn't for him, I
wouldn't have had a job.

1599
01:20:36,265 --> 01:20:38,101
I mean that machine
would just stop running

1600
01:20:38,134 --> 01:20:40,870
all of a sudden, and we'd
all be standing around

1601
01:20:40,904 --> 01:20:43,039
scratching our heads
trying to figure it out.

1602
01:20:43,072 --> 01:20:44,607
And, he would just walk up.

1603
01:20:44,640 --> 01:20:46,485
In a matter of seconds, it
was up and running again.

1604
01:20:46,509 --> 01:20:48,044
(laughing)

1605
01:20:48,077 --> 01:20:49,913
When I bought this
company, first thing I said

1606
01:20:49,946 --> 01:20:52,415
I was gonna do was try and
get him that promotion,

1607
01:20:52,448 --> 01:20:54,984
but the law prevented it.

1608
01:20:55,018 --> 01:20:56,628
I don't know how this
company would've made it

1609
01:20:56,652 --> 01:20:59,488
through those early
years without him.

1610
01:20:59,522 --> 01:21:01,790
To tell you the truth, I don't
know how I'll make it now

1611
01:21:01,824 --> 01:21:03,592
without you.

1612
01:21:03,626 --> 01:21:06,996
You've got those
same qualities, son.

1613
01:21:07,030 --> 01:21:11,267
Go home Jarvis, I'll
see you in the morning.

1614
01:21:11,300 --> 01:21:13,136
In the morning, sir?

1615
01:21:14,370 --> 01:21:16,672
What about the second shift?

1616
01:21:16,705 --> 01:21:20,009
I need my new paper press
manager to be well rested.

1617
01:21:20,043 --> 01:21:22,178
He's got a long
day ahead of him.

1618
01:21:22,211 --> 01:21:23,279
(laughing)

1619
01:21:23,312 --> 01:21:24,480
[Jarvis] Yes sir.

1620
01:21:24,513 --> 01:21:26,315
[Mr. Munson]
You bet, good man.

1621
01:21:26,349 --> 01:21:27,316
Yes sir!

1622
01:21:27,350 --> 01:21:30,719
(happy orchestral music)

1623
01:21:55,211 --> 01:21:57,613
[Mr. Spurling] And, all is
well in this little Mississippi

1624
01:21:57,646 --> 01:21:58,881
town.

1625
01:21:58,914 --> 01:22:01,884
Jarvis got his promotion
and lived out a dream

1626
01:22:01,917 --> 01:22:04,320
that his father never could have

1627
01:22:04,353 --> 01:22:07,756
with his best friend
Jericho by his side.

1628
01:22:09,092 --> 01:22:12,461
So grandpa, whatever
happened to those evil men,

1629
01:22:12,495 --> 01:22:14,497
Marcel, Toby, and Larry?

1630
01:22:15,831 --> 01:22:19,668
Well let's just
say they were welcome

1631
01:22:19,702 --> 01:22:23,206
with open arms at their
new place of residence.

1632
01:22:23,239 --> 01:22:25,074
(laughing)

1633
01:22:25,108 --> 01:22:26,909
Fortunately for you
boys, Jim Crow passed

1634
01:22:26,942 --> 01:22:28,544
a little bit too early.

1635
01:22:28,577 --> 01:22:30,679
Governors already mandated
that all jailhouses

1636
01:22:30,713 --> 01:22:31,880
be integrated.

1637
01:22:35,951 --> 01:22:37,720
I just got one question.

1638
01:22:37,753 --> 01:22:39,688
What you in here for?

1639
01:22:42,358 --> 01:22:45,028
(country music)

1640
01:22:48,297 --> 01:22:51,600
And, Jarvis and Jericho
lived happily ever after,

1641
01:22:51,634 --> 01:22:53,102
the end.

1642
01:22:53,136 --> 01:22:57,406
Well now actually, that
was only the beginning.

1643
01:22:57,440 --> 01:23:00,143
(dramatic music)

1644
01:23:18,827 --> 01:23:20,963
Hey Jarvis, everything okay?

1645
01:23:20,996 --> 01:23:23,066
You're usually the
first man here.

1646
01:23:23,099 --> 01:23:26,602
Yes sir, Jericho's
car broke down again.

1647
01:23:28,071 --> 01:23:30,539
But, believe me it was an
easier walk to work today.

1648
01:23:30,573 --> 01:23:32,108
(laughing)

1649
01:23:32,141 --> 01:23:33,452
But hey, I've been
saving for a car

1650
01:23:33,476 --> 01:23:34,953
ever since I got this
job so I won't have

1651
01:23:34,977 --> 01:23:36,612
to worry about that much longer.

1652
01:23:36,645 --> 01:23:39,315
I know that, and I'm
proud of your patience.

1653
01:23:39,348 --> 01:23:41,617
But, I've been thinking
about a way to help you.

1654
01:23:41,650 --> 01:23:43,386
Seeing as I sold the
company last week,

1655
01:23:43,419 --> 01:23:45,321
I'll be retiring soon.

1656
01:23:45,354 --> 01:23:49,192
Well I didn't wait too
much longer to do this.

1657
01:23:52,295 --> 01:23:53,496
What's this, boss?

1658
01:23:53,529 --> 01:23:54,739
That's your new
ride to work, son.

1659
01:23:54,763 --> 01:23:56,732
Got the car at the
house all ready to go.

1660
01:23:56,765 --> 01:23:58,343
You just come on by and
pick it up this afternoon

1661
01:23:58,367 --> 01:23:59,502
after the shift ends.

1662
01:23:59,535 --> 01:24:00,836
Thank you, Mr. Munson.

1663
01:24:00,869 --> 01:24:01,770
Don't mention it.

1664
01:24:01,804 --> 01:24:03,005
Thank you, sir!

1665
01:24:03,038 --> 01:24:05,007
Least I can do for a
hard worker like you.

1666
01:24:05,040 --> 01:24:07,210
Jericho, I got me a car!

1667
01:24:08,977 --> 01:24:10,213
I got me a car!

1668
01:24:14,350 --> 01:24:15,384
Oh my damn.

1669
01:24:18,954 --> 01:24:20,165
Isn't this what you've
been waiting for

1670
01:24:20,189 --> 01:24:21,924
all your damn life?

1671
01:24:21,957 --> 01:24:22,957
Yes.

1672
01:24:25,894 --> 01:24:26,894
My, my, my!

1673
01:24:28,897 --> 01:24:30,299
Do you like it?

1674
01:24:30,333 --> 01:24:31,200
Shit yeah!

1675
01:24:31,234 --> 01:24:33,969
I mean yes sir, we love it.

1676
01:24:34,002 --> 01:24:35,171
Don't we, Jarvis?

1677
01:24:35,204 --> 01:24:36,172
Mr. Munson, it's
the most beautiful car

1678
01:24:36,205 --> 01:24:37,540
I've ever seen.

1679
01:24:37,573 --> 01:24:38,707
I agree.

1680
01:24:38,741 --> 01:24:40,008
I thought you would like it.

1681
01:24:40,042 --> 01:24:42,245
(laughing)

1682
01:24:43,246 --> 01:24:45,114
But, that ain't it.

1683
01:24:45,148 --> 01:24:47,383
Come on, come on over here.

1684
01:24:51,086 --> 01:24:53,189
(crying)

1685
01:24:59,362 --> 01:25:00,639
Well I think y'all
are gonna like this one

1686
01:25:00,663 --> 01:25:02,465
just as well.

1687
01:25:02,498 --> 01:25:04,576
I keep the oil changed, start
it up every now and then,

1688
01:25:04,600 --> 01:25:05,868
but it runs great.

1689
01:25:05,901 --> 01:25:07,503
Been in the family for years.

1690
01:25:07,536 --> 01:25:10,273
(dramatic music)

1691
01:25:19,748 --> 01:25:20,583
(gun firing)

1692
01:25:20,616 --> 01:25:23,586
(glass shattering)

1693
01:25:25,788 --> 01:25:28,391
(yelling)

1694
01:25:28,424 --> 01:25:31,694
Mr. Munson, where'd
you get this car?

1695
01:25:35,063 --> 01:25:38,033
Mr. Munson, I said where
did you get this car?

1696
01:25:38,066 --> 01:25:41,103
Like I said Jarvis, it's
been in the family for years.

1697
01:25:41,136 --> 01:25:42,538
It was my first car.

1698
01:25:42,571 --> 01:25:43,915
Mr. Munson, forgive
me if I don't take

1699
01:25:43,939 --> 01:25:46,375
too kindly to this here gift.

1700
01:25:47,543 --> 01:25:51,046
This car was used in the
murder of my brother,

1701
01:25:51,079 --> 01:25:52,748
my only brother.

1702
01:25:52,781 --> 01:25:56,285
Daddy was never the
same after that night.

1703
01:25:58,487 --> 01:26:01,890
In fact, I don't even
think he smiled again

1704
01:26:01,924 --> 01:26:04,727
even on the happiest of days.

1705
01:26:04,760 --> 01:26:06,629
My brother was my mother
and father's only hope

1706
01:26:06,662 --> 01:26:10,233
to go off to college
and study medicine.

1707
01:26:10,266 --> 01:26:13,336
He was gonna be a
doctor, Mr. Munson.

1708
01:26:14,970 --> 01:26:17,540
I'll never forget
the day we found him

1709
01:26:17,573 --> 01:26:19,475
hanging from that tree.

1710
01:26:21,009 --> 01:26:23,812
I'm so sorry
for your loss son.

1711
01:26:25,248 --> 01:26:27,483
I remember that night also.

1712
01:26:28,984 --> 01:26:31,487
I never thought he would've...

1713
01:26:32,821 --> 01:26:37,125
I never should have
trusted Johnny with my car.

1714
01:26:37,159 --> 01:26:38,159
Johnny?

1715
01:26:39,695 --> 01:26:42,164
You talking about
old man Edwards?

1716
01:26:42,197 --> 01:26:45,968
Yeah unfortunately,
he's my brother-in-law.

1717
01:26:47,303 --> 01:26:49,838
He said he was gonna
celebrate after getting

1718
01:26:49,872 --> 01:26:52,675
that promotion at the mill.

1719
01:26:52,708 --> 01:26:55,110
You know they'd always
despised your father

1720
01:26:55,143 --> 01:26:57,813
for all the good he'd
done around the factory.

1721
01:26:57,846 --> 01:26:59,982
And, he never thought Johnny
deserved that promotion

1722
01:27:00,015 --> 01:27:00,816
over him.

1723
01:27:00,849 --> 01:27:02,351
And, he was right.

1724
01:27:03,886 --> 01:27:06,722
But, when he filed
that complaint,

1725
01:27:10,058 --> 01:27:12,628
he always said he was
gonna teach him a lesson.

1726
01:27:12,661 --> 01:27:13,829
I just shrugged it off.

1727
01:27:13,862 --> 01:27:17,199
I never thought it
would amount to much.

1728
01:27:18,200 --> 01:27:20,369
I guess I'm as much to blame.

1729
01:27:20,403 --> 01:27:23,138
(dramatic music)

1730
01:27:30,879 --> 01:27:32,981
Have you no shame?

1731
01:27:33,015 --> 01:27:35,384
What in God's name
have you done, Johnny?

1732
01:27:35,418 --> 01:27:39,555
What's the matter
there, brother-in-law?

1733
01:27:39,588 --> 01:27:41,557
You ain't never been
out on an evening ride

1734
01:27:41,590 --> 01:27:45,894
with your young'un, had a
deer jump out on you before?

1735
01:27:45,928 --> 01:27:48,864
Marcel, you go inside
and get ready for bed.

1736
01:27:48,897 --> 01:27:49,698
Yes, uncle Clark.

1737
01:27:49,732 --> 01:27:50,733
Right now.

1738
01:27:50,766 --> 01:27:53,402
(dramatic music)

1739
01:27:53,436 --> 01:27:55,804
(laughing)

1740
01:27:55,838 --> 01:27:56,838
Marcel!

1741
01:27:59,408 --> 01:28:02,244
He had an aneurism
later that night.

1742
01:28:02,277 --> 01:28:04,847
He used to have so much to say,

1743
01:28:05,848 --> 01:28:08,584
now he can't say a word.

1744
01:28:08,617 --> 01:28:11,587
Been trapped in a broken
body for 20 years now.

1745
01:28:11,620 --> 01:28:12,688
I'm gonna kill him.

1746
01:28:12,721 --> 01:28:13,556
No, man, no.

1747
01:28:13,589 --> 01:28:14,890
I'm gonna kill him!

1748
01:28:14,923 --> 01:28:16,024
No, Jarvis.

1749
01:28:16,925 --> 01:28:18,927
Jarvis, I know it hurt.

1750
01:28:18,961 --> 01:28:22,998
I know you're upset,
but killing that man

1751
01:28:23,031 --> 01:28:25,868
would be a blessing
to him right now.

1752
01:28:25,901 --> 01:28:28,937
God, done already took
justice out on him

1753
01:28:28,971 --> 01:28:30,773
before he could go to
bed at night and smile

1754
01:28:30,806 --> 01:28:32,307
about what he did.

1755
01:28:33,642 --> 01:28:36,144
Think about what grandma said.

1756
01:28:38,313 --> 01:28:40,349
Jericho's right Jarvis.

1757
01:28:40,383 --> 01:28:44,553
There ain't nothing I can say
to bring your brother back,

1758
01:28:46,288 --> 01:28:48,957
but there is something I can do.

1759
01:28:48,991 --> 01:28:51,494
(jazzy music)

1760
01:29:03,606 --> 01:29:05,240
Man, can you believe
Mr. Munson gave me

1761
01:29:05,273 --> 01:29:07,109
his prized possession?

1762
01:29:08,411 --> 01:29:10,212
I mean can you believe that?

1763
01:29:10,245 --> 01:29:12,581
It wasn't his fault,
but to take responsibility

1764
01:29:12,615 --> 01:29:16,785
for his family, now that's
a good man there, Jarvis.

1765
01:29:18,353 --> 01:29:20,222
Say he said he left
something else for me

1766
01:29:20,255 --> 01:29:22,290
in the glove compartment.

1767
01:29:22,324 --> 01:29:23,324
Open it up.

1768
01:29:30,533 --> 01:29:32,367
Got your name on it.

1769
01:29:40,342 --> 01:29:43,111
(dramatic music)

1770
01:29:53,822 --> 01:29:56,191
(laughing)

1771
01:29:56,224 --> 01:29:57,224
Yes!

1772
01:29:58,527 --> 01:29:59,527
Yes!

1773
01:30:02,731 --> 01:30:04,066
Thank you Jesus!

1774
01:30:06,334 --> 01:30:07,334
Woo!

1775
01:30:09,805 --> 01:30:11,540
[Jericho] Can you
believe that, Jarvis?

1776
01:30:11,574 --> 01:30:12,975
Mr. Munson sold
you the paper mill

1777
01:30:13,008 --> 01:30:17,179
for about the same price
as a pack of pork chops.

1778
01:30:17,212 --> 01:30:19,548
Well I'm gonna tell you
right now as my new boss,

1779
01:30:19,582 --> 01:30:21,884
I'm gonna be late
tomorrow morning.

1780
01:30:21,917 --> 01:30:24,553
[Mr. Spurling] And,
that was how it went.

1781
01:30:24,587 --> 01:30:26,855
(clapping)

1782
01:30:29,692 --> 01:30:32,194
Wow grandpa, that was amazing.

1783
01:30:32,227 --> 01:30:35,564
I mean it was like we were
right there in the struggle.

1784
01:30:35,598 --> 01:30:39,735
Oh Percy, Mr. Spurling you
are a fantastic storyteller

1785
01:30:39,768 --> 01:30:42,571
and all with one single picture.

1786
01:30:42,605 --> 01:30:44,873
I want to thank you for
sharing that with us.

1787
01:30:44,907 --> 01:30:46,742
Let's give Mr.
Spurling another hand.

1788
01:30:46,775 --> 01:30:49,077
(clapping)

1789
01:30:52,581 --> 01:30:55,518
(dramatic music)

1790
01:30:55,551 --> 01:30:57,496
[Mr. Spurling Voiceover]
You didn't think I was gonna

1791
01:30:57,520 --> 01:31:00,489
let you get out of here without
knowing who I am, did you?

1792
01:31:00,523 --> 01:31:02,991
(laughing)

1793
01:31:03,025 --> 01:31:05,260
My name is Elijah Spurling.

1794
01:31:06,629 --> 01:31:08,196
That's a nasty
